      "content": "but why is \"fiscal discipline\" always the starting point? it sounds like you're framing debt reduction as the only \"correct\" way to approach the economy, while treating social programs as a risk that needs to be controlled. isn't it a bit biased to claim debt reduction is the \"immediate priority\" when lots of economists argue that the real priority should be addressing inequality and underfunding public services? why can't you just say both are equally valid paths instead of making debt the main focus?",
